  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has developed significantly over the past several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in the 1970s\n- United States passed the Bank Secrecy Act of 1970, requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Aimed to combat organized crime and drug trafficking financial networks\n\n2. International Developments:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop global AML standards\n- 1990: United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs provided first international framework\n- Encouraged countries to criminalize money laundering related to drug trafficking\n\n3. Expanded Legislation:\n- 1990s: Money laundering laws broadened beyond drug-related crimes\n- U.S. passed Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Criminalized money laundering as a separate federal offense\n- Expanded predicate crimes beyond drug trafficking\n\n4. Post-9/11 Regulations:\n- Patriot Act of 2001 significantly enhanced AML/Counter-Terrorist Financing regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Expanded investigative powers for financial institutions\n\n5. Modern Global Standards:\n- Increasingly comprehensive international legal frameworks\n- More sophisticated tracking and reporting mechanisms\n- Continuous updates to address emerging financial technologies",
